dog’s health and can lead to acute kidney failure. Some other common symptoms to look out for are diarrhea, lethargy and stomach pain. So if you’re trick or treating this year, skip the house with the bad candy; you’ll all be happier.\n<h4><strong>Candy</strong></h4>\nEven non-chocolate candies can be toxic for your dog’s health due to an ingredient known as xylitol. This spooky, sugar-free sweetener can be found in lollipops, gum, Jello-O, and some brands of peanut butter. Xylitol can cause a dangerous insulin increase in dogs which can lead to a sharp decrease in blood sugar and cause hypoglycemia.\n\nKeep your dog safe this year by keeping that bag of treats out of reach. Instead of chocolate or candy, chop up some&nbsp;<a href=\"http://digest.thefarmersdog.com/top-14-dog-friendly-snacks/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">fresh treats</a>&nbsp;for your dog to enjoy, like apples or carrots. They may not be as decadent as your treats, but your dog’s health is a far better investment. Someone needs to be around to keep you safe during those scary movies.', 'KEEP YOUR DOG SAFE FROM THESE TRICKS IN HALLOWEEN TREATS', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '2804-revision-v1', '', '', '2019-09-24 09:28:35', '2019-09-24 07:28:35', '', 2804, 'http://foodog.test/2019/09/24/2804-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
